IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: R-24 equipped with in-car camera and body-worn camera. Case# 23-MSP-007028 Defendant: Robert Lewis Hawkins Jr. Date of Birth: 10/21/1983 Date of Arrest: 02/24/2023 Time of Arrest: 0209 hours DUI #: 23-114 Certificates and Training *Trained in administering standardized field sobriety tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration *Certified Emergency Medical Technician by the Maryland Institute of Emergency Medical Services Systems *Certified RADAR/LIDAR operator by the Maryland State Police *Certified License Plate Reader (LPR) operator by the Maryland State Police Vehicle In Motion (Phase 1) On February 24th, 2023 at approximately 0156 hours I, Trooper Sigman #7376, currently assigned to the Golden Ring Barrack, was on routine patrol of the outer loop of 695 prior to Belair Road in lane 3 when I observed a black pickup truck in my rear view mirror traveling at a high rate of speed traveling in lane 4. That pickup truck, a black Ford F-150 bearing Maryland registration of 1ET9952, then passed my marked police car unsafely to the right at a high rate of speed. I then got behind the F-150 and paced it at 85mph in a posted 55mph zone for greater than 4/10 of a mile. My vehicle speedometer was calibrated and found to be functioning properly prior to the date and time of the stop. I then observed the F-150 take the ramp to Belair Road. While taking the ramp which veered right off of 695 the F-150 had its left turn signal activated for an unknown reason. Upon nearing the end of the ramp the F-150 crossed the solid white line separating the ramp and Belair Road and made a prohibited lane change. I then activated my emergency equipment and initiated a traffic stop on the Black Ford F-150 bearing Maryland registration of 1ET9952. The F-150 then stopped in lane 3 of Belair Road north of Putty Hill Avenue. Personal Contact (Phase 2) I then made a drivers side approach of the Ford F-150 bearing Maryland registration of 1ET9952. Upon arriving at the drivers window I could immediately detect the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the vehicle. I then identified myself, the reason for the stop, and requested the drivers license. The driver was then identified by his Maryland drivers license as Robert Lewis Hawkins Jr. (10/21/1983). Hawkins then stated that he was driving home to his girlfriend and was coming from So Baltimore which he later explained was a night club in Baltimore City. Upon speaking with Hawkins I observed that he had slurred speech as well as glassy eyes. I then asked Hawkins how many alcoholic beverages he had consumed prior to driving. Hawkins replied just one. I then requested Hawkins to exit and walk to the front of his vehicle. Upon stepping out of his vehicle I observed that Hawkins displayed gait ataxia. I also detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person. I again asked Hawkins how many alcoholic beverages he had consumed prior to driving. Hawkins advised that he had consumed One margarita. I then asked Hawkins if he would consent to standardized field sobriety testing. Hawkins agreed. Pre-Arrest Screening (Phase 3) The evaluation was performed in front of Hawkins vehicle in lane 3. The surface was dry, level, and free from any obvious debris. The weather was clear and approximately 56 degrees. Lighting conditions consisted of streetlights, and overhead lights, and my vehicles takedown lights. My vehicles front facing emergency lights were deactivated for the duration of the field sobriety tests. Hawkins appeared to be in good physical condition and did not display any visible injuries and or defects. I asked Hawkins the following questions: Injuries- none Medical conditions- none Medications- none Glasses or contacts- none Alcoholic beverages- one margarita Controlled dangerous substance- none Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (6/6) The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. The test was properly explained. I then began the test. I did not observe any resting nystagmus. The tip of my pen was used as the stimulus. Lack of Smooth Pursuit - present in both eyes Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - present in both eyes Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - present in both eyes *Vertical Gaze Nystagmus - not present in either eye During the test Hawkins stated this feels great, I was waiting for this. Walk and Turn (6/8 clues observed) Prior to Hawkins performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. I asked Hawkins if he had any questions. Hawkins stated that he understood the test. Instructional Stage: Steps out of starting position. After stepping out of the starting position Hawkins had difficulty getting back into the starting position. Walking Stage (1st Nine): Steps off line Misses heel to toe Raises arms for balance Takes 10 steps Walking Stage (2nd Nine): Raises arms for balance Steps off line Misses heel to toe Takes 12 steps Turn: Incorrect, uses the toes off both feet to pivot in one abrupt motion counterclockwise One Leg Stand (3/4) Prior to Hawkins performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Hawkins advised that he understood the test. Instructional Stage: Sways from side to side Balance and Count Stage Seconds 0-10: Sways from side to side Raises arms for balance Seconds 11-20: Sways from side to side Raises arms for balance Puts foot down Seconds 21-30: Puts foot down Sways from side to side Raises arms for balance I then offered my PBT to Hawkins . Hawkins agreed and the results were .12 on serial #1205990 Arrest Based on the following, I had probable cause to believe Hawkins was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol: *Traveling 30mph over the posted speed limit *Passing a marked police car at a high rate of speed *Making a prohibited turn across a solid white line *Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from the vehicle *Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage on his breath and person *Glassy eyes *slurred speech *Gait ataxia *Poor SFST At this time Hawkins was placed under arrest for DUI. Hawkins was then handcuffed, searched, and placed in the front seat of R-24 and seat belted inside. Hawkins was then mirandized. Hawkins was then transported to the Golden Ring Barrack. Hawkins vehicle was then parked in an alleyway off of Belair Road with his permission. Once at the Golden Ring Barrack Hawkins was walked inside and placed in the intoximeter room. A physical copy of the DR15 was placed in front of him and the audio version was played aloud. At the conclusion of the audio Hawkins stated that he did not wish to take the intoximeter test. The time of the refusal was 0248 hours 20-Minute Observation Period: N/A Intoximeter Result: N/A Hawkins was then issued a DR15A. Hawkins was then released to his mother in the front lobby lot of the Golden Ring Barrack. The appropriate citations were then certified mailed to Hawkins listed address. The citations issued in error were voided All above events occurred in Baltimore County, Maryland.
